Analyzing and Visualizing Nobel Prize Winners¶

On this page, you can see a code I wrote with the guide of Rasmus Bth from DataCamp Projects. I used pandas and seaborn to manipulate and visualize data from a CSV file taken from Kaggle.

Alfred Nobel founded the Nobel prizes, and in his will, he asked that the prize will be given "to those who, during the preceding year, have conferred the greatest benefit to humankind". The data is of all the Nobel Prize winners from 1901 to 2016.

# I wanted to see when the USA started dominating the Nobel charts. 
# Calculate the proportion of USA born winners per decade
nobel['usa_born_winner'] = nobel['birth_country'] == 'United States of America'
nobel['decade'] = (np.floor(nobel['year'] / 10) * 10).astype(int)
prop_usa_winners = nobel.groupby('decade', as_index=False)['usa_born_winner'].mean()

# Display the proportions of USA born winners per decade
prop_usa_winners

# That did not tell me much so I wanted to visualize the data.
# Setting the plotting theme
sns.set()
# and setting the size of all plots.
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = [11, 7]

# Plotting USA born winners
ax = sns.lineplot(x='decade', y='usa_born_winner', data=prop_usa_winners)

# Formatting 
from matplotlib.ticker import PercentFormatter
ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(PercentFormatter(1.0))
ax.set_title('USA-Born Nobel Prize Winners')

# The above data does not make me happy. I want to see this trend over the years.

# Code I used before
nobel['decade'] = (np.floor(nobel['year'] / 10) * 10).astype(int)

# Calculating the proportion of female winners per decade
nobel['female_winner'] = nobel['sex'] == 'Female'
prop_female_winners = nobel.groupby(['decade', 'category'], as_index=False)['female_winner'].mean()

# Plotting female winners with % winners on the y-axis
ax = sns.lineplot(x='decade', y='female_winner', hue='category', data=prop_female_winners)
ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(PercentFormatter(1.0))
ax.set_title('Proportion of Female Nobel Prize Winners')

# I now wanted to find how old are individuals when they receive the prize. For this, I first had to convert the given birth date from a string ("1934-07-04") so that I can work and visualize the data. 
# Converting birth_date from String to datetime
nobel['birth_date'] = pd.to_datetime(nobel['birth_date'])

# Calculating the age of Nobel Prize winners
nobel['age'] = nobel['year'] - nobel['birth_date'].dt.year

# Plotting the age of Nobel Prize winners
sns.lmplot(x='year', y='age', data=nobel, lowess=True, 
           aspect=2, line_kws={'color' : 'black'})
# Add a title to the Figure
ax.set_title("Age of Nobel Prize Winners")
Out[45]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Age of Nobel Prize Winners')

Note¶

One reason I find the above figure very interesting is because I can see that around the year 1940, there were no winners. That is of course because World War II took place from 1939-1945.
